subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Distinguished from other members of the 

O. bakeri

group by having a dark, almost black body coloration (
Fig. 12A
) and mesoscutum with lateral lobes dorsally smooth (
Fig. 12F
). It is most similar to 

O. texana

but lacks a depression in the midlobe of the mesoscutum (
Fig. 12F
), lacks a medial carina on the propodeum (
Fig. 12F
), and has a smooth to imbricate upper mesepimeron (
Fig. 12C
).
